    <abstract id="aspace_dd3ae12388b599bebf868e81875587e0">Milton Ost (1917-1987) and Ruth Ost (1928-2022) were actively engaged in progressive matters throughout their lives, and were members of the Communist Party of the United States of America (CPUSA) until leaving soon after 1956. Milton Ost was a writer who worked in direct mail advertising. Milton wrote skits for CPUSA rallies, as well as a play titled <emph render="italic">The Warsaw Ghetto Uprising</emph>, which was read and performed at left-wing trade union events. Milton also wrote articles for <emph render="italic">Jewish Currents</emph>. Ruth Ost worked on the Management Committee of <emph render="italic">Jewish Currents</emph>, and for 30 years was the Office Manager of Lobsenz-Stevens public relations firm. The Ost Family Papers (dated 1948-2014) consist of materials created and collected by Milton and Ruth Ost documenting their personal lives and political engagements. Materials in this collection include copies of Milton's writings, including a script for <emph render="italic">The Warsaw Ghetto Uprising</emph>; documents from Milton's memorial service at Riverside Memorial Chapel; and photographs from Steve Nelson's 72nd birthday celebration, where he was honored at the Veterans of the Abraham Lincoln Brigade Luncheon. The collection also includes correspondence, including correspondence between Ruth and her sister Faith Bonosky, the wife of Philip Bonosky. Ruth and Faith's letters help document the Bonosky's family life, including the time period that the Bonoskys lived in the USSR. Other correspondents include Henry Foner, Steve Nelson, and friends and family expressing their condolences following Milton's death.</abstract>
